# Emily LLM Provider Rules

## Provider Hierarchy
- All providers implement `BaseProvider` (`emily_chat/models/providers/base.py`)
- OpenAI-compatible providers extend `OpenAICompatibleProvider` (`_openai_compat.py`) ã only override what differs
- Each provider lives in its own file: `emily_chat/models/providers/<name>.py`

## Required Interface
- `async def stream(messages, system_prompt, settings, model_spec) -> AsyncIterator[StreamChunk]` ã the core streaming method
- `async def validate_key(api_key) -> bool` ã verify API key validity
- `async def close()` ã release httpx client resources

## StreamChunk Protocol
- Every chunk must be one of: `thinking`, `text`, `usage`, `stop`, `error`
- Text chunks: `StreamChunk(type=ChunkType.TEXT, content="...", tokens=1)`
- Thinking chunks: `StreamChunk(type=ChunkType.THINKING, content="...", tokens=1)`
- Usage chunks: metadata dict with `prompt_tokens`, `completion_tokens`, `reasoning_tokens`
- Error chunks: `StreamChunk(type=ChunkType.ERROR, content="error message")` ã never raise exceptions mid-stream
- Stop chunk: `StreamChunk(type=ChunkType.STOP)` ã signals clean stream end

## SSE Parsing (`_parse_sse_line`)
- Lines not starting with `data:` are ignored (comments, event names, empty)
- `data: [DONE]` -> `StreamChunk(type=STOP)`
- Malformed JSON -> log warning and skip, never crash the stream
- Extract `delta.content` for text, `delta.reasoning_content` for thinking
- Extract `usage` from the final SSE chunk (includes `completion_tokens_details.reasoning_tokens`)

## Think Tag Extraction
- Models that embed reasoning in `<think>...</think>` tags (DeepSeek R1, Qwen3, GLM, Kimi) use `ThinkTagExtractor`
- Override `_uses_think_tags(model_id) -> bool` to enable per-model
- The extractor is a stateful buffer that handles tags split across chunk boundaries
- Always call `extractor.flush()` at stream end to emit any remaining buffered content

## httpx Client Management
- One `httpx.AsyncClient` per provider instance, created in `__init__`
- Set explicit timeouts: `httpx.Timeout(120.0, connect=10.0)` ã LLM generations can be slow
- Set `Authorization: Bearer <key>` in default headers
- Provider instances are cached in `_PROVIDERS` / `_cache` dicts ã lazy construction on first use

## Model Registry
- Every model Emily can use is a `ModelSpec` in `EMILY_MODEL_REGISTRY` (`registry.py`)
- `ModelSpec` is `@dataclass(frozen=True)` ã immutable after creation
- Fields: `display`, `provider`, `model_id`, `context`, `thinking`, `vision`, `input_usd`, `output_usd`, `speed`, `tier`, `best_for`, `notes`
- Dynamic models (Ollama auto-discovery, OpenRouter custom) use `register_dynamic_model(key, spec)`

## Cost Tracking
- Call `estimate_cost(model_spec, tokens_in, tokens_out, tokens_thinking)` after every generation
- Pricing is per-million tokens in `ModelSpec.input_usd` / `output_usd`
- Free models have `input_usd=0.0, output_usd=0.0`

## Provider Factory
- `get_provider(model_spec)` returns a cached provider instance
- API keys read from environment variables (e.g., `OPENAI_API_KEY`, `OPENROUTER_API_KEY`)
- `ProviderUnavailableError` raised when key is missing ã handled gracefully by the auto-router

## Auto-Router
- `EmilyAutoRouter.route(request)` selects the best available model
- Decision tree: context size -> multimodal -> thinking -> code -> creative -> language -> speed -> cost -> balanced
- Only considers models whose provider has a configured API key (`_has_api_key()`)
- Free OpenRouter models serve as last-resort fallbacks in every chain

## Adding a New Provider
1. Create `emily_chat/models/providers/<name>.py` extending `OpenAICompatibleProvider` (or `BaseProvider` for non-OpenAI APIs)
2. Add the env var to `_ENV_MAP` in `provider_factory.py`
3. Add the provider branch to `_build_provider()` in `provider_factory.py`
4. Add the dotted path to `_PROVIDER_CLASSES` in `streaming_engine.py`
5. Add `ModelSpec` entries to `EMILY_MODEL_REGISTRY` in `registry.py`
6. Add the category to `_MODEL_CATEGORIES` in `emily_chat/ui/top_bar.py`
7. Add free models to auto-router fallback chains in `auto_router.py`
